 knowing when or if it would come. Drawing on a wide range of memoirs, art, poetry, and contemporary records, The Gods Left First reconstructs their experience of captivity, return, and encounter with a postwar Japan that now seemed as alien as it had once been familiar. In a broader sense, this study is a meditation on the meaning of survival for Japan’s continental repatriates, showing that their memories of involvement in Japan’s imperial project were both a burden and the basis for a new way of life.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aConcentration camp inmateszRussia (Federation)zSiberiavBiography. 0aConcentration campszRussia (Federation)zSiberiaxHistoryy20th century. 0aImperialismxSocial aspectszEast AsiaxHistoryy20th century. 0aInternment camp inmateszRussia (Federation)zSiberiavBiography. 0aInternment campszRussia (Federation)zSiberiaxHistoryy20th century. 0aJapanesezEast AsiaxHistoryy20th century. 0aJapanesezRussia (Federation)zSiberiavBiography. 0aJapanesezRussia (Federation)zSiberiaxHistoryy20th century. 0aRepatriationzJapanxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / Asia / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z978311069042240uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052095657540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520956575423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520956575/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles